RIYADH: Authorities in Saudi Arabia foiled an attempt to smuggle thousands of amphetamine pills and arrested two suspects, the General Directorate of Narcotics Control said on Wednesday.  إحباط محاولة تهريب (403,000) قرص إمفيتامين مخدر مخبأة داخل شحنة فول في قوالب بلاستيكية على هيئة حبات الفول، وضبطها بحوزة شخصين والقبض عليهما بمحافظة جدة.#الحرب_على_المخدرات pic.twitter.com/FIJNX0ghFO — وزارة الداخلية (@MOISaudiArabia) May 25, 2022 Spokesman Maj. Mohammed Al-Nujaidi said security officials who monitor drug smuggling and distribution networks that target the Kingdom intercepted 403,000 amphetamine tablets. They were found in the possession of a Syrian national and a Saudi citizen in Jeddah, hidden in a shipment of fake plastic bean pods, he added. The two men were referred to the Public Prosecution. Al-Nujaidi said that the Ministry of Interior’s security forces, in coordination with the Zakat, Tax and Customs Authority, will continue to work to uncover plots to smuggle narcotics into the Kingdom and arrest those responsible.